# Wi-Fi specific rules

# Weak signal
signal_dbm < -80 | Weak Wi-Fi signal | Move closer to the router or remove obstacles

# Power saving mode
power_save = on | Power saving mode enabled | Disable power save on Wi-Fi adapter (`sudo iwconfig <interface> power off`)

# Fallback suggestions if no specific cause matches, with practical commands
!any | Try: | Check your router interface for channel interference (use gateway IP: `ip route | grep default`)
!any | Try: | Ensure Wi-Fi devices are line-of-sight
!any | Try: | Reboot the router (`sudo reboot` if you can access it)
!any | Try: | If all devices are affected, contact your ISP
!any | Try: | Make sure the correct Wi-Fi password is entered on all devices
!any | Try: | Temporarily disable any firewall or VPN that may block connectivity (`sudo ufw disable` or disable VPN)
!any | Try: | Test with another device to see if the issue is device-specific
!any | Try: | Try switching between 2.4GHz and 5GHz bands (check router settings)
!any | Try: | Move the router to a more central location
!any | Try: | Update router firmware to the latest version (check router manufacturer instructions)

# Optional: commands if specific errors are matched
!any | Try: | Restart NetworkManager service (`sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager`)
!any | Try: | Check interface status (`nmcli device status` or `ip link`)
!any | Try: | Force DHCP renew (`sudo dhclient -r && sudo dhclient`)
!any | Try: | Scan for networks manually (`nmcli dev wifi rescan && nmcli dev wifi list`)
